paste evaluation/appraisal/*/capital*.md | grep -Eo '\[[[:digit:]]{1,3}%]' | grep -Eo '[[:digit:]]+' | paste - - - - | nl | awk '
function min(a,b) { return a == 0 ? (b == 0 ? 101 : b) : (a <= b ? a : (b == 0 ? 101 : b)); }
function max(a,b) { return a >= b ? a : b; }
function min3(a,b,c) { return min(min(a,b),c); }
function max3(a,b,c) { return max(max(a,b),c); }
function min4(a,b,c,d) { return min(min(min(a,b),c),d); }
function max4(a,b,c,d) { return max(max(max(a,b),c),d); }
min4($2,$3,$4,$5) != 101 { print $1, min4($2,$3,$4,$5), max4($2,$3,$4,$5), max4($2,$3,$4,$5)-min4($2,$3,$4,$5); }
'

Have to account for 4 files, some of which are named differently! (Also some
slighy formatting tweaks.)

In the future, this version is too cumbersome. Use the #lang-parsed data and
build a CSV or something.

Output slightly tweaked to make more sense: https://gist.github.com/benknoble/c9329d2eab131ec4eb8fa2cb886d4415

Here's computing an average:

paste evaluation/appraisal/*/capital*.md | grep -Eo '\[[[:digit:]]{1,3}%]' | grep -Eo '[[:digit:]]+' | paste - - - - | nl | awk '{ print $1 + 2, ($2+$3+$4+$5)/4; }'

